Certainly! Here's a simple HTML/JS code snippet that creates a colorful website with two jokes as placeholders. The jokes have been replaced with two actual jokes.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>My Joke Website</title>
<style>
  body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    background-color: #f4f4f4;
    color: #333;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .jokes {
    background-color: #fff;
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 20px;
    margin: 20px;
  }
  .joke {
    background-color: #f4f4f4;
    padding: 10px;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .joke p {
    margin: 0;
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="jokes">
  <div class="joke">
    <h2>Joke 1</h2>
    <p>Why did the tomato turn red?</p>
    <p>Because it saw the salad dressing!</p>
  </div>
  <div class="joke">
    <h2>Joke 2</h2>
    <p>Why did the scarecrow win an award?</p>
    <p>Because he was outstanding in his field!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
  // Add any JavaScript code you want to run here
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

This code will create a simple webpage with a white background and two jokes. The jokes are styled with a light gray background and a darker gray border to make them stand out. You can replace the jokes with your own content or add more features as needed.
